Catherine Anne Tynan, a daughter of Mary Ann and Patrick Tynan of Dedham, Mass., was married last evening to Brendan Keith O'Dwyer, the son of Marianna and Brian O'Dwyer of New York. Janet Weston, a friend of the bride's family, was authorized by the Commonwealth of Massachusetts to officiate at Gedney Farm in New Marlborough, Mass.

Mrs. O'Dwyer, 31, teaches English to ninth- and 11th-graders at the Kent School in Kent, Conn. She graduated magna cum laude from Colby College and received a Master of Fine Arts from Warren Wilson College in Asheville, N.C.

Her father, who retired as an algebra and Latin teacher at Dedham Country Day School in Dedham, Mass., is the secretary of the board of trustees of the Massachusetts Horticultural Society and on the board of overseers of WGBH, the public television station in Boston. Her mother, also retired, was the director of regulatory affairs and a partner in Wellington Management Company, an investment management company in Boston. She is the vice chairwoman of Brigham & Women's Hospital in Boston.
Mr. O'Dwyer, 28, is a carpenter and cabinetmaker in Pawling, N.Y. He graduated from Purchase College of the State University of New York.

His mother is an associate vice chancellor for presidential searches and evaluations at the State University of New York. His father, a senior partner in O'Dwyer & Bernstien, a law firm in New York, was a member of the President's Commission on White House Fellowships in 1999 and 2000.
The bridegroom is a grandson of the late Paul O'Dwyer, the president of the New York City Council from 1973 to 1977.
